<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Climate is mostly gradual — but not always.</p>
  <p>Some thresholds, once crossed, can't easily be uncrossed: <strong>West Antarctic Ice Sheet collapse</strong>, <strong>AMOC (Atlantic Meridional Overturning Circulation) slowdown</strong>, <strong>Amazon dieback</strong>, <strong>permafrost methane release</strong>. These are tipping points. Today: what makes a tipping point "tipping" vs. gradual, and which ones are real risks vs. tail-risk possibilities.</p>
  <p>Then we apply <a href="/units/unit-1/">Unit 1's</a> feedback-loop muscle to climate-specific feedbacks. <strong>Ice-albedo feedback</strong>: less ice means darker surface, more absorbed radiation, more warming, less ice — positive (amplifying). <strong>Water-vapor feedback</strong>: warmer atmosphere holds more water vapor, which is itself a greenhouse gas — positive. <strong>Permafrost-methane feedback</strong>: warming thaws permafrost, releasing trapped methane, more warming — positive. The <a href="/ai-partners/systems-diagrammer/">Systems Diagrammer</a> from Unit 1 helps with sign-and-direction notation.</p>
  <p>The block closes with the debate that feeds your <a href="/units/unit-4/assessment-chennai-climate-brief/">Climate Brief's Recommendations section</a>: do tipping-point uncertainties make YOUR Brief's Recommendations more cautious (don't risk crossing thresholds) or more aggressive (act now while gradual mitigation is still possible)? Either position is defensible; the move is to <em>defend</em> it with evidence.</p>
</section>

